  "text": "Although studies have been done to explore the damaging potential of RONS associated with the host response [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , the possibility that S. pneumoniae might directly induce oxidative damage to DNA had not been explored. Studies focused on respiratory, as well as intestinal pathogens [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , call attention to the importance of microbial-induced DNA damage as an important dimension of pathogenicity. For example, Pseudomonas aeruginosa has been shown to induce oxidative DNA damage in lung cells accompanied by significant tissue injury [CITATION_5] . These findings",
